column1: #text=The simplest way to make cake is with a mix .
#text=Just open the box and mix in some eggs , some water , and maybe some oil .
#text=Grease two round pans by rubbing them with a stick of butter , pour in the batter , bake as directed and you are done .
#text=Making a coffee cake with Bisquick baking mix is only slightly harder , but the product is not really what some people call a cake .
#text=There are also delicious cakes that are really store-bought baked goods layered with ice cream .
#text=But for a birthday , an actual homemade cake is traditional .
#text=I make such a cake in two separate bowls and then combine the mixtures .
#text=I also use a stand mixer , though even that can feel like cheating .
#text=First , I lay out all my ingredients , and preheat the oven .
#text=I prepare two round pans , by greasing with butter or pan spray , sprinkling with flour and shaking out the excess .
#text=Next , I cream the butter and sugar together , on a medium-high mixer setting .
#text=Then I mix in eggs and then vanilla .
#text=In a separate bowl , I combine the flour , baking powder , and salt .
#text=Now , I add the dry ingredients to the butter mixture , a little at a time , alternating with the milk , while I mix at medium high .
#text=It is important not to over mix , so I only combine until the lumps are gone and it looks glossy .
#text=I fill the pans evenly , and place in the oven so they do not touch and one is not directly above the other .
#text=When the time is up , or they smell done , I press lightly in the center of the cake with one finger .
#text=If it springs back it is done .
#text=I cool on a wire rack , run a knife around the edge , invert it on a plate to remove while still warm .
#text=I frost liberally , and I do n't forget the candles .
